<ArticleTitle>Apolipoprotein L-I promotes trypanosome lysis by forming pores in lysosomal membranes.</ArticleTitle>
<Pagination>
<MedlinePgn>469-72</MedlinePgn>
</Pagination>
<Abstract>
<AbstractText>Apolipoprotein L-I is the trypanolytic factor of human serum. Here we show that this protein contains a membrane pore-forming domain functionally similar to that of bacterial colicins, flanked by a membrane-addressing domain. In lipid bilayer membranes, apolipoprotein L-I formed anion channels. In Trypanosoma brucei, apolipoprotein L-I was targeted to the lysosomal membrane and triggered depolarization of this membrane, continuous influx of chloride, and subsequent osmotic swelling of the lysosome until the trypanosome lysed.</AbstractText>
</Abstract>
